from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler     # preprocessing class in scikit-learn used for standardizing features by removing the mean and scaling to unit variance
In [8]:
# Load in mnist 
# It returns two tuples:
(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = mnist.load_data()     

#training -  Training images and their corresponding labels
#testing - Testing images and their corresponding labels

# Reshape to each image to a row vector and column vector
x_train_rowvector = np.reshape(x_train, (-1, 28*28))       #reshape into 28x28 pixels
x_train_colvector = np.copy(x_train_rowvector).T           #creates a copy of the input array to prevent modifying the original data.
x_test_rowvector = np.reshape(x_test, (-1, 28*28))
x_test_colvector = np.copy(x_test_rowvector).T

In [11]:
# Apply Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)
U, S, Vt = np.linalg.svd(x_train_colvector_sample2000, full_matrices=False)      #linalg= computes the Singular Value Decomposition of a matrix

# input matrix for which SVD is calculated
#u- The left singular vectors of x_train_colvector_sample2000
#vt - The right singular vectors of x_train_colvector_sample2000
#s - The singular values of x_train_colvector_sample2000

#full_matrices=Fales -argument specifies whether to compute the full-sized or reduced-sized SVD. When full_matrices=False, it computes the reduced SVD
In [12]:
# Number of singular values to retain (dimensionality reduction)
k = 50      #represents the number of singular values to retain after performing dimensionality reduction.

# Reconstruct the compressed data using k singular values
X_compressed = U[:, :k] @ np.diag(S[:k]) @ Vt[:k, :]

#U[:, :k]: This selects the first k columns of the left singular vectors matrix U.

#np.diag(S[:k]): This creates a diagonal matrix with the first k singular values. 

#Vt[:k, :]: This selects the first k rows of the transposed right singular vectors matrix Vt. 
#@: The @ symbol is used for matrix multiplication.

In [17]:
# Calculate the covariance matrix
covariance = np.cov(x_train_colvector_sample2000)     #function computes the covariance matrix of the input data
In [18]:
# Calculate the eigenvalues and the eigenvectors for the covariance matrix
eigenvalues, eigenvectors = np.linalg.eig(covariance)      #calculates the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a square matrix.

# eigenvalues variable will store an array of eigenvalues
#eigenvectors variable will store a 2D array where each column represents an eigenvector
In [19]:
# Get the real part of the eigenvalues and eigenvectors only
eigenvalues = np.real(eigenvalues)    #calculates the real part of the eigenvalues
eigenvectors = np.real(eigenvectors)  #calculates the real part of the eigenvectors.
In [20]:
# Project original data onto eigenvectors
pca = np.dot(x_train_colvector_sample2000.T, eigenvectors)     #performs the dot product between the transpose of x_train_colvector_sample2000 and the eigenvectors.

# Get only the first two columns for the first two principal components
pca = pca[:, 0:2]
In [21]:
# Calculate u, s, v
u, s, v = np.linalg.svd(x_train_colvector_sample2000, full_matrices=False)     #It decomposes the matrix into u, s, and v,
# Set all singular values greater than the first two to 0
for i in range(2, s.shape[0]):
    s[i] = 0
# Calculate the reduced dimensions with svd
svd_cords = np.diag(s) @ v      # reconstructs the data points in the reduced-dimensional space.

#Sort the training images by label

x_list= [0] * 10
y_list = [0] * 10
for i in range(10):
    # Get x and y values in each label by the coordinate in the list
    x_list[i] = (x_train_colvector[:, y_train == i])     #For each digit i, this line filters the columns (images) from x_train_colvector
    y_list[i] = (y_train[y_train == i])       #For each digit i, this line filters the columns (images) from x_train_colvector
In [24]:
#Calculate the Mean Image for Each Digit

means_list = [0] * 10
for i in range(10):
    means_list[i] = np.mean(x_list[i], axis=1)     #this line calculates the mean image by computing the mean along the columns of the images in x_list[i]
In [25]:

    # Show singular image

# Iterate through all the digits
for i in range(10):
    print("#################################################################")
    print("#################################################################")
    print("Visualizing Singular Images for " + str(i))
    print("#################################################################")
    print("#################################################################")
    # Calculate the SVD for that digit
    u, s, v = np.linalg.svd(x_list[i], full_matrices=False)     #calculates the SVD for the images corresponding to the current digit i. 
    # Visualize the first three singular images
    for j in range(3):
        print("Visualizing Singular Image Number " + str(j + 1))
        # Get the singular image    
        image = u[:, j]     #extracts the j-th singular vector (singular image) from the left singular vectors matrix u.
        # Show singular image
        plt.imshow(image.reshape(28, 28), cmap="Greys")    #extracts the j-th singular vector (singular image) from the left singular vectors matrix u.
        plt.show()
        plt.close()
